We start by noting that – in our records – the “Fixed Assets” balance is first set on 2023‑12‑31 by the initial entry:
 • Initial row (type “Fixed Assets”) shows an amount of 8,000,000.00.

Then during the reporting period additional “transactions” affect the fixed‐asset book value through depreciation. (Other “Purchase” transactions you see in the listing are for items like Business Meal Sets, Room items, etc. They are not treated as fixed assets.) We do see depreciation entries that reduce the fixed‐asset value. In this file there are two Depreciation transactions:
 • Depreciation20240101001 has amount 45,746.47.
 • Depreciation20240201002 has amount 45,741.88.

These two together reduce the fixed assets by:
  45,746.47 + 45,741.88 = 91,488.35

Thus, the ending fixed assets are computed as:
  8,000,000.00 – 91,488.35 = 7,908,511.65

We now present the answer in the required JSON format.

--------------------------------------------------

{
  "solution": {
    "Fixed Assets Initial Value": "8000000.00",
    "Fixed Assets End Value": "7908511.65"
  }
}
